Making starters for tonight’s family dinner. This is my best papaya salad ever. 

The secret to delicious papaya salad is tamarind, lime & palm sugar. It’s a complex balance of sours and sweet. This version is vegan.

I learned to cut the papaya thinly using a mandolin and sharpening my knife skills. 

Papaya Salad for 2

*Mix together papaya, pounded green beans, carrot, cilantro and carrot in large bowl. 

 • 1½ cups thinly julienned green papaya
 • 2-3 long beans, cut into 1-inch pieces
 •  2 thinly sliced carrot 
 •  1/4 cup cilantro chopped 
 •  ½ cup grape tomato halves or a small tomato cut into wedges

* pound and mix together sauce ingredients 

 • 1 cloves garlic - pound
 • Thai chilies, to taste 
 • 1 ½ Tbsp palm sugar, finely chopped
 • 2 Tbsp fresh lime juice 
 • 2 tsp tamarind juice 
 • 1 ½ Tbsp soy sauce or fish sauce
 •  1 heaping Tbsp small dried shrimp(optional)

Garnish with peanuts 
 • 3 Tbsp roasted peanuts 

Add sauce to salad ingredients, mix well, garnish with peanuts.

I didn’t have a traditional mortar for this dish. So I used my small mortar and pounded each item separately and then mixed in bowl.

Creamy, low salt Asparagus soup for lunch
1 tsp avocado oil
1 cup onion
1 tablespoon chopped garlic
3 cups chopped asparagus 
11/2 cups water
4 oz juiced stems-(optional) 
Salt to taste( I’m cutting down)
1/2 cup soaked cashews

Sauté onion and garlic with oil till translucent. Add asparagus & it’s juice( I juiced the hard stems) 1 cup water.

Cook till opaque, allow to cool down. In blender add soaked cashews and asparagus mixture, blend till really creamy, pour back into pan and heat to desired hotness (😆is that a word) 

On the @medicalmedium asparagus challenge 😁

The funniest way to grow food is to naturalize it. What does that mean? How would you do that? 

Well you have to scatter seeds. Veggie seeds work better on fertile soil. Not all seeds can be scattered but the smaller mustard like seeds do well as they don’t need to be buried or buried too deep. Yes size of seed matters and the bigger the seed you can go deeper(future video) 

Edible weeds are the easiest to start with, as is carrots, lettuces, fenugreek, calendula, parsley, arugula.

Plantain leaves have been used by many different cultures as a remedy for coughs, colds, wounds, skin conditions, and more. Their anti-inflammatory, wound healing, and anti-infective properties have been confirmed in studies.

The youngest leaves will be the most tender and have a high nutritional value. They can be eaten like greens in salads, soups, etc. More mature leaves typically contain a higher concentration of beneficial medicinal compounds, but leaves get tougher and stronger in flavor the older they are.

This information is from euphoricherbals.com/blogs/news/the-many-benefits-of-plantain-leaf

Just unboxed Spiced Jaggery from @twobrothersorganicfarmsindia and it delicious. My aunt had a farm and used to make this for us yearly, I haven’t had it for a long time. 

I love the full rich, deep flavor of this sugar.  The Two Brothers brand is made traditionally, in giant iron Kadhais(woks) okra is used to remove impurities and make it smooth. 

Then ghee is added, and it spiced with dry ginger powder, Green cardamon and Fennel seeds. 

I love it as an after dinner digestive, in my chai. What uses can you think of for Spiced Jaggery?

Fall & winter are a great time to gather leaves. Leaves make the most nutrient rich compost; leaves capture the energy of the sun and nutrients from the soil. 

I compost all my leaves. Either on the ground in fabric bags or a compost pit. 

Crush the leaves and it will compost faster. If you have any questions please let me know. This is a great season to collect leaves.
